Rain forests, those with heavy annual rainfall, and which contain valuable flora and fauna on the verge of extinction, exist not only in South and Central America, but also in China and Africa.
African countries are uniting to adopt protection policies.
China is establishing and expanding nature reserves, closing intrusive small companies and sugar factories, moving farms, arresting poachers, stopping illegal lumbering, and protecting gibbons, which have high research value.
A Chinese scientist says protection of the rain forest means protecting an important gene.
Malaysia is cooperating with Brazil in the launch of satellites to monitor their tropical forests.
